1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,960
To become a good backend or infrastructure developer,

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:05,340
You absolutely have to read the research papers in your field.

3
00:00:05,340 --> 00:00:08,500
That's because 80% of the standard interview questions you'll face are actually derived from these very papers.

4
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:12,700
So, the best way to learn is to go straight to the source material.

5
00:00:12,700 --> 00:00:15,610
Instead of just chewing on the leftovers that other people have already picked through.

6
00:00:15,610 --> 00:00:19,530
In this video, I'm going to share some papers that I personally think are really great.

7
00:00:19,530 --> 00:00:20,610
The paper is actually pretty straightforward.

8
00:00:20,610 --> 00:00:23,610
And chances are, you've heard of most of the real-world applications of these papers.

9
00:00:25,210 --> 00:00:27,910
You can grab them in the comment section after you like, coin, and favorite the video!

10
00:00:27,910 --> 00:00:33,840
Alright, first up we have HotRing, an optimization method for HashMap's chaining addressing proposed by Ali.

11
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:36,080
This is done by constructing a circular linked list.

12
00:00:36,080 --> 00:00:41,990
Plus, it dynamically moves hot nodes to the front of the list to mitigate the performance drop caused by hash collisions.

13
00:00:41,990 --> 00:00:44,730
In fact, Ali's Tail has used this algorithm for optimization.

14
00:00:44,730 --> 00:00:48,070
Next up is RocksDB, the renowned embedded, on-disk key-value store.

15
00:00:48,070 --> 00:00:51,420
and some papers on the development history of RocksDB.

16
00:00:51,420 --> 00:00:54,880
For those interested in storage, you can also check out the WiscKey paper.

17
00:00:54,880 --> 00:00:56,830
The WiscKey paper.

18
00:00:56,830 --> 00:00:58,630
The paper on Vertical Paxos is one that I think is severely underrated.

19
00:00:58,630 --> 00:01:02,290
In my opinion, this is a paper whose influence has been seriously underestimated.

20
00:01:02,290 --> 00:01:05,620
The most common disaster recovery solution we see is actually just a service registry.

21
00:01:05,620 --> 00:01:07,980
and then add a master-slave synchronization mechanism for high availability.

22
00:01:07,980 --> 00:01:12,259
This paper essentially formalizes the master-slave synchronization as a type of consensus algorithm.

23
00:01:12,259 --> 00:01:15,179
I've taken a look at the underlying principles of High Availability in Kafka.

24
00:01:15,179 --> 00:01:18,490
And the design philosophy from this paper is likely what they're using.

25
00:01:18,490 --> 00:01:22,420
The lease mechanism was first defined in this very paper.

26
00:01:22,420 --> 00:01:27,320
It's now widely used in areas like heartbeat detection and the Kubernetes architecture.

27
00:01:27,320 --> 00:01:33,089
Next up, PacificA. This is the highly acclaimed high-availability algorithm used by Elasticsearch.

28
00:01:33,089 --> 00:01:34,749
But from a personal perspective,

29
00:01:34,749 --> 00:01:40,250
I think the algorithm in this paper shares some similarities with the Vertical Paxos we just mentioned.

30
00:01:40,250 --> 00:01:43,850
Unfortunately, the paper doesn't describe the connection between the two.

31
00:01:44,710 --> 00:01:46,970
SWIM is an algorithm that uses gossip for service discovery.

32
00:01:46,970 --> 00:01:50,820
Consul actually uses this algorithm under the hood.

33
00:01:50,820 --> 00:01:55,330
But compared to Redis's service discovery algorithm, which can't even handle a few thousand machines,

34
00:01:55,330 --> 00:01:58,410
I actually proposed a feature for Redis before, and the design was based on this very paper.

35
00:01:58,410 --> 00:02:01,770
Right.

36
00:02:01,770 --> 00:02:04,210
I'm sure you're all familiar with TiDB, the renowned masterpiece from PingCAP.

37
00:02:04,210 --> 00:02:06,259
the very pillar of the renowned HTAP.

38
00:02:06,259 --> 00:02:11,179
It talks about the engineering implementation of the Raft algorithm in HTAP systems.

39
00:02:11,179 --> 00:02:13,079
The paper, "Paxos vs. Raft," gives us...

40
00:02:13,079 --> 00:02:19,870
when describing the operations of Raft and Paxos using the same terminology,

41
00:02:19,870 --> 00:02:23,530
So, what exactly are the differences between Paxos and the more mainstream Raft?

42
00:02:23,890 --> 00:02:28,070
On the Parallels between Paxos and Raft

43
00:02:28,070 --> 00:02:30,050
This is a paper from the team at Shanghai Jiao Tong University.

44
00:02:30,050 --> 00:02:36,780
It establishes a formal correspondence between Paxos and Raft through a refinement mapping.

45
00:02:36,780 --> 00:02:39,940
That's because in academia, most of the research is on Paxos.

46
00:02:39,940 --> 00:02:43,870
But in the field of engineering, most people are actually implementing the Raft algorithm.

47
00:02:43,870 --> 00:02:51,689
This means that for any given paper on Paxos, you can use this one to map and optimize its concepts onto Raft.

48
00:02:51,689 --> 00:02:54,969
PolarFS is the distributed file system from Alibaba.

49
00:02:54,969 --> 00:03:00,230
The system also introduces the Parallel Raft algorithm.

50
00:03:00,230 --> 00:03:03,910
This solves the log hole problem in Raft that occurs during out-of-order commits.

51
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:08,020
X-Engine is Alibaba's OLTP storage engine.

52
00:03:08,020 --> 00:03:11,030
This is the tech stack designed to handle massive traffic spikes like the Double 11 shopping festival.

53
00:03:11,030 --> 00:03:15,670
It addresses these challenges through optimizations at various levels.

54
00:03:15,870 --> 00:03:18,210
Dynamic Resource Allocation Using Virtual Machines for Cloud Computing Environment.

55
00:03:18,210 --> 00:03:20,430
Using virtual machines for cloud...

56
00:03:20,430 --> 00:03:21,910
Computing environment.

57
00:03:21,910 --> 00:03:25,310
It uses traditional, non-AI algorithms for resource scheduling.

58
00:03:25,310 --> 00:03:28,830
One paper that I'm personally a huge fan of is one from the team at Peking University.

59
00:03:28,830 --> 00:03:33,199
In this day and age, where it seems like every paper is about using AI to manage machine loads,

60
00:03:33,199 --> 00:03:35,400
I still find it to be a real breath of fresh air.

61
00:03:35,400 --> 00:03:39,300
So, the papers we're covering in this video are a bit more niche compared to the last batch.

62
00:03:39,300 --> 00:03:42,200
But they are all papers that I've personally read and found to be pretty good.

63
